# Freeze (`@`) interaction with the buffered O(N) temporal lowering.
#
# The buffered lowering computes an operator once and indexes it by state, so
# it is only valid for operators whose value is a function of the state index.
# A freeze breaks that for anything under it that names the frozen state, and
# these requirements pin the resulting semantics from the outside.
#
# Trace (expr_freeze.csv), real states:
#   si=1  t=0     a=true  b=true
#   si=2  t=1000  a=true  b=false
#   si=3  t=2000  a=true  b=false

data    a:  boolean;
data    b:  boolean;

# Inside `t@(...)`, `t.b` denotes b at the *frozen* state, so it is constant
# for the whole of the inner backward scan.  With a constant rhs `c` the Since
# recurrence val[i] = c || (a[i] && val[i-1]) with base false collapses to `c`
# itself, so the whole expression collapses to plain `b`.
G(t@(Ss(a, t.b)) == b);

# The point of the previous line: it must NOT agree with the unfrozen Ss(a,b).
# Over this trace a holds throughout and b holds at the first state, so
# Ss(a,b) is true everywhere while b is not.  If the inner Ss were ever
# precomputed into a per-state buffer -- which would evaluate `t.b` at the
# scanned state rather than the frozen one -- these two would agree and this
# requirement would fail.
!G(t@(Ss(a, t.b)) == Ss(a, b));

# A freeze whose body never mentions the frozen name is semantically identical
# to no freeze at all.  This is the case the lowering is free to buffer, and
# buffering it must not change the answer.
G(t@(Ss(a, b)) == Ss(a, b));

# A temporal operator that *contains* a freeze is itself evaluated once per
# state like any other, so it stays eligible for the buffered path; the
# restriction applies only to operators nested under the freeze.  Sanity-check
# that the outer operator still produces the right answer.
#   inner collapses to b => Us(b, b) == b at every state
G(Us(t@(Ss(a, t.b)), t@(Ss(a, t.b))) == b);
